  "prompt": "Is there a maximum limit for a transaction via Net Banking through an SBI account?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a maximum limit for transactions via Net Banking through an SBI (State Bank of India) account. However, **the exact limit varies depending on several factors**:\n\n*   **Your Account Type:** Different account types (e.g., savings, current) may have different default transaction limits.\n*   **Your Profile Type:** Some accounts have a view-only access vs a transaction access.\n*   **Your Existing Limit Configuration:** SBI allows you to customize your transaction limits within certain ranges. You might have already set a lower limit than the bank's default.\n*   **Transaction type**: IMPS, NEFT, RTGS have different maximum limits.\n*   **Third Party Transfer Limits**: Different types of third-party transfer may have different maximum limits.\n*   **Security reasons**: SBI may, on rare occasions, restrict limits for security reasons.\n\n**General Guidelines (Keep in Mind):**\n\n*   **Typically, the default transaction limit for SBI Net Banking ranges from INR 50,000 to INR 10 lakhs per day.**\n*   **You can usually increase (or decrease) this limit online through your SBI Net Banking account.** Look for options like \"Manage Limits,\" \"Change Transaction Limits,\" or similar settings. You may need to use your profile password or OTP.\n*   **For higher limits, you might need to visit your SBI branch and submit a written request.**\n\n**How to Check Your Current Limit:**\n\n1.  **Log in to your SBI Net Banking account.**\n2.  **Look for a section related to \"My Accounts & Profile,\" \"Manage Limits,\" or \"Transaction Limits.\"** The exact navigation might vary slightly depending on the version of SBI's online banking platform.\n3.  **You should be able to see your current daily transaction limits for different types of transactions (e.g., fund transfers to other SBI accounts, fund transfers to other banks via NEFT/RTGS/IMPS, UPI).**\n\n**Important Notes:**\n\n*   **Always prioritize security:** Be cautious about setting excessively high limits if you don't need them.\n*   **Contact SBI directly:** For the most accurate and up-to-date information about your specific account's transaction limits, contact SBI customer care or visit your nearest branch.\n*   **SBI may change its policies:** The limits can change from time to time, so it's always a good idea to check periodically.\n\nIn conclusion, while there's a limit, it's not a single fixed number. Check your account settings or contact SBI to know the exact limit that applies to you.",
